of an American religion that serves to unite the social order, Levinson maintains that its sacred role can result in conflict, fragmentation, and even war. To Levinson, the Constitution's value lies in the realm of the discourse it sustains: a uniquely American form of political rhetoric that allows citizens to grapple with every important public issue imaginable. In a new afterword, Levinson looks at the deepening of constitutional worship and attributes the current widespread frustrations with the government to the static nature of the Constitution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawxReligious aspects. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh  aAmerican political community.  aAmerican religion.  aCatholics.  aChristian doctrine.  aProtestants.  aU.S. Constitution.  aUS Constitution.  aaffirmation.  acivil religion.  aconstitutional faith.  aconstitutional worship.  alaw professors.  alaw school.  alaw.  aloyalty.  amarriage.  amorality.  aoaths.  aquasi-religious system.  areligious faith.  arule of law.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400839872zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400839872423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400839872.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aP